{"type":"message","id":"bbc4b0fb","parentId":"42ca89aa","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:59:50.178Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_qlczc7gwaxyp_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 105914\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: a (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action I can take to advance the goals.\r\n\r\nCurrent state:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 COMPLETE\r\n- CFI Analysis done - found that 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0), only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7)\r\n- Next pending action: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe key insight from CFI_RESULTS.md is that:\r\n1. CFI=0 invariants are metaprogramming artifacts (noise)\r\n2. CFI>=0.7 invariants are true causal anchors (research trajectory)\r\n3. Current compression uses frequency only - this causes signal loss\r\n\r\nThe pending experiment is to implement CFI-weighted compression and compare it to frequency-only baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nTo run this experiment, I need:\r\n1. Access to the invariant data (from previous pulse analysis)\r\n2. Implement CFI-weighted scoring\r\n3. Compare prediction quality\r\n\r\nLet me look at what files exist and what the next concrete step is. The immediate action should be to implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\nI should check what data I have available and implement the experiment. Let me create a plan for this experiment.\r\n\r\nGiven I'm stateless and this is a fresh pulse, I need to:\r\n1. Look at existing research files to understand the data structure\r\n2. Implement a simple CFI-weighted compression test\r\n3. Document results\r\n\r\nLet me start by examining what invariant data exists and then implement the experiment.\r\n\r\nActually, let me be practical here. The most concrete next step is to implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment. I'll need to:\r\n1. Read the existing invariant analysis to understand format\r\n2. Create a simple test comparing CFI-weighted vs frequency-only compression\r\n3. Document results\r\n\r\nLet me write a concrete action: implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment script.\r\n\r\nThe experiment should:\r\n1. Load the invariants from the research files\r\n2. Score them by CFI vs frequency\r\n3. Compare which better predicts \"important\" patterns (high-frequency research terms)\r\n\r\n\r\n4. Document findings\r\n\r\nI'll create a simple Python script to analyze the compression methods, focusing on how CFI weighting impacts preservation of critical research information. The script will generate comparative metrics to validate the approach.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI_RESULTS.md reveals that frequency-based compression causes 81.9% mean signal loss. The next critical step is implementing CFI-weighted compression to test if causal anchoring improves prediction quality over frequency-only baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a concrete CFI-weighted compression experiment script that compares CFI vs frequency scoring for next-pulse prediction quality. This directly addresses the pending \"CFI-weighted compression experiment\" task.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n`\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24  \r\n**Goal:** Compare CFI-weighted vs frequency-only compression for next-pulse prediction\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI >= 0.7 (causal anchors) will predict next-pulse important tokens better than frequency alone.\r\n\r\n## Method\r\n1. Extract invariants with (freq, CFI) pairs from `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n2. Score tokens by two methods:\r\n   - **Frequency:** weight = freq / max_freq\r\n   - **CFI-weighted:** weight = CFI * log(freq + 1)\r\n3. Compare top-K preservation of high-frequency research terms\r\n\r\n## Data Source\r\nTokens from pulse_2026-03-24 analysis with paired (freq, CFI) values.\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted compression retains ~5.7% of tokens (CFI>=0.7) vs frequency baseline.\r\nIf these tokens better predict next-pulse content, CFI is the correct metric.\r\n\r\n## Files\r\n- `scripts/cfi_compression_test.py` - experiment script\r\n- `state/compression_comparison.md` - results\r\n\r\n## Status\r\n- [x] Design complete\r\n- [ ] Implement script\r\n- [ ] Run comparison\r\n- [ ] Document results\r\n`\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n`\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:59:41\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774364390176}}
